Wire PermissionEnforcer into the tool registry

`runtime/src/permission_enforcer.rs` and the per-command classifier
`classify_bash_permission` (`tools/src/lib.rs:1844`) were dead code in the
production CLI: the registry constructed at
`rusty-claude-cli/src/main.rs:6867` is never given an enforcer via
`with_enforcer(...)`, so `tools/lib.rs::maybe_enforce_permission_check` is
a no-op. The only gate that actually fired was `PermissionPolicy::
authorize_with_context` in `ConversationRuntime::execute_turn` — and that
gate consults the tool's static `required_permission`, which is
`DangerFullAccess` for every tool in `mvp_tool_specs`. Under the shipped
`dontAsk` default mode the gate was satisfied trivially.

Construct a `PermissionEnforcer` from the resolved policy and attach it
to the registry between policy build and the `CliToolExecutor::new` call.
This activates the per-command bash classification path in the registry
layer in addition to the existing `ConversationRuntime` gate. The new
behavior only bites when the active mode is below `DangerFullAccess`
(i.e., once patch 0001 has dropped the default to `ReadOnly`).

Also re-export `PermissionEnforcer` and `EnforcementResult` from the
runtime crate so downstream consumers (this CLI, future tooling) don't
need to reach into `runtime::permission_enforcer::*` paths.
